Wavelength associated with Excitation-Emission Matrix (EEM) data, which is the distance between peaks in a light wave, measured in nanometers (nm). It includes Excitation Wavelength (the light directed at the sample to trigger fluorescence) and Emission Wavelength (the light emitted by the sample in response). Wavelength values, typically in the 200700 nm range, are essential for constructing the EEM data matrix, where each excitation-emission pair corresponds to a fluorescence intensity value.

Type of grab sample associated with the solid char sample (300C; 600C; endchar; completecombustion or muffle). "Muffle" means char sample came from material burnt in crucible in a closed muffle furnace. "300C" and"600C" indicates sample was grabbed off the open-air burn table around a temperature of 300 and 600 degrees celcius respectively. "Completecombustion" char samples were ash grab samples from the burn table in-which visually all vegetation had been consumed in the burn. "Endchar" was a homogenized sample of all the remaining char on the burn table after the burn. See BSLE_Burn_Protocol.pdf for more information.

A time series of the average depth of the reach was created in two steps. First; the average depth of the stream reach was measured via transects; sonar; or public sources. This created a reach-average depth at a single point in time. In order to convert this into a time series; we calculated a time series of depth-offsets based on a single point water pressure datalogger and a local barometric pressure logger. Barometric pressure was subtracted from absolute pressure to get water pressure; which was then converted to depth at a single-point in the stream. The difference between each single-point depth time series measurement and the single-point depth at the reference time (time at which reach depth was measured via transect; sonar; or public sources) was used as the depth offset. This offset for the single-point depth was added to the average stream reach depth to create the time series.

Unit: Dissolved oxygen units vary by metric.
Definition: Statistical metrics generated for dissolved oxygen (mg/L) data collected with Minidot Logger 1 (i.e.; sample) using a specified InstallationMethod_ID. Five metrics were calculated for each sample at every site; including lm_slope; R_square; RMSE; Mean; and Range; which are also defined in the data dictionary. In each summary statistics file; each site is associated with five rows of summary statistics data (one row for each metric).

Unit: Dissolved oxygen percent saturation units vary by metric.
Definition: Statistical metrics generated for dissolved oxygen percent saturation data collected with Minidot Logger 1 (i.e.; sample) using a specified InstallationMethod_ID. Five metrics were calculated for each sample at every site; including lm_slope; R_square; RMSE; Mean; and Range; which are also defined in the data dictionary. In each sensor summary statistics file; each site is associated with five rows of summary statistics data (one row for each metric).

Error messages produced by streamMetabolizer. The two errors in this data are "data don't start when expected" and "data don't end when expected". These errors are included when the indicated day does not have a full 24 hours of data. This is often the case for (1) the day of deployment (2) the day of retrieval and (3) partway through deployment. Data was removed partway through deployment when other sampling occurred which disturbed the sensors. The model ignores the data from the days with these errors.

Methods information is embedded in first few rows of respective data file with methods codes that are defined in the file that ends in "Methods_Codes.csv".

Mean ammonium reported as ammonium (rather than as nitrogen). 5-digit prefix typically refers to a US Geological Survey (USGS) parameter code in the column headers of this data package. The USGS does not have a parameter code for ammonium that is appropriate, so 00000 is used as a placeholder to keep column name formats consistent. For each sampling event (e.g. SPS_005_ION), the NPOC values of each of the three biological replicates (e.g. SPS_005_ION-1; SPS_005_ION-2; SPS_005_ION-3) are averaged. Any replicate values that were identified as an outlier or were above/below the limit of detection are not included in the mean. Outliers were identified using distance based outlier detection. If the set of replicates had a coefficient of variation of 30 percent or higher, the outlier was identified by calculating the distance between each of the replicates. The replicate with the highest distance to the other two replicates was flagged as an outlier. The "Mean_Missing_Reps" column indicates if a mean does not include all three replicates using a TRUE/FALSE flag where TRUE indicates one or more replicates are missing from the mean.

For each sampling event (e.g. CM_005_ION) the values of each of the three biological replicates (e.g. CM_005_ION-1; CM_005_ION-2; CM_005_ION-3) are averaged. Any replicate values that were identified as an outlier or were above/below the limit of detection are not included in the mean. Outliers were identified using distance based outlier detection. If the set of replicates had a coefficient of variation of 30 percent or higher the outlier was identified by calculating the distance between each of the replicates. The replicate with the highest distance to the other two replicates was flagged as an outlier. The "Mean_Missing_Reps" column indicates if a mean does not include all three replicates using a TRUE/FALSE flag where TRUE indicates one or more replicates are missing from the mean. If the set of replicates had a coefficient of variation of 30 percent or higher in the picomoles per gram calculation the outlier was identified by calculating the distance between each of the replicates. The replicate with the highest distance to the other two replicates was flagged as an outlier. The "Mean_Missing_Reps" column indicates if a mean does not include all three replicates using a TRUE/FALSE flag where TRUE indicates one or more replicates are missing from the mean. Methods information is embedded in first few rows of respective data file with methods codes that are defined in the file that ends in "Methods_Codes.csv".

A sample name with -solid appended refers to data collected on solid ground char.

Standard deviation of compound specific delta 13 C in leachate samples. Standard deviation of stable isotopic composition of carbon (delta carbon-13/carbon-12) in Benzenepentacarobyxlic acid (B5CA). Standard deviation was calculated from the three leaches per sample (i.e. BSLE_001A, BSLE_001B, BSLE_001C) or from the standards; the larger value of the two is reported. This calculated standard deviation is reported for every leachate and, therefore, is the same value for the three leachates used in the calculation. Sample names have"-filt0.2" appended indicating it was filtered through a 0.7 micrometer filter and then a 0.2 micrometer filter. Methods information is embedded in first few rows with methods codes that are defined in the file that ends in "Methods_Codes.csv".

Standard deviation of compound specific delta 13 C in leachate samples. Standard deviation of stable isotopic composition of carbon (delta carbon-13/carbon-12) in Benzenepentacarobyxlic acid (B5CA). Standard deviation was calculated from the maximum standard deviation of the standard curves for the sample run. Therefore, the reported standard deviation is the same for all samples. Methods information is embedded in first few rows with methods codes that are defined in the file that ends in "Methods_Codes.csv".

Wavelength associated with Excitation-Emission Matrix (EEM) data, which is the distance between peaks in a light wave, measured in nanometers (nm). It includes Excitation Wavelength (the light directed at the sample to trigger fluorescence) and Emission Wavelength (the light emitted by the sample in response). Wavelength values, typically in the 200700 nm range, are essential for constructing the EEM data matrix, where each excitation-emission pair corresponds to a fluorescence intensity value.
